{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti (Laws of Manu), Chapter 8.**\n\nThis ancient Hindu legal text prescribes graduated penalties for theft according to the fourfold social order (*varnas*), with the fine (or \"guilt\") scaling upward: eightfold for a Shudra (the lowest order), sixteenfold for a Vaishya (the merchant/farmer class), thirty-twofold for a Kshatriya (the warrior class), and sixty-fourfold (or a full hundred, or even twice sixty-four) for a Brahmana (the priestly class). The heightened penalty for the Brahmana is explicitly justified because \"he is a knower of the good and bad qualities of that act.\"[^1][^2]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, *Chapter 8*, [p-fc6559](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-fc6559).\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, *Chapter 8*, [p-30e5e8](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-30e5e8).",
